<!-- Content -->

<p>
<b>Alchimie de la douleur</b><br>
</p>

<p>
L'un t'&eacute;claire avec son ardeur,<br>
L'autre en toi met son deuil, Nature!<br>
Ce qui dit &agrave; l'un: S&eacute;pulture!<br>
Dit &agrave; l'autre: Vie et splendeur!<br>
</p>

<p>
Herm&egrave;s inconnu qui m'assistes<br>
Et qui toujours m'intimidas,<br>
Tu me rends l'&eacute;gal de Midas,<br>
Le plus triste des alchimistes;<br>
</p>

<p>
Par toi je change l'or en fer<br>
Et le paradis en enfer;<br>
Dans le suaire des nuages<br>
</p>

<p>
Je d&eacute;couvre un cadavre cher,<br>
Et sur les c&eacute;lestes rivages<br>
Je b&acirc;tis de grands sarcophages.<br>
</p>
<p>&mdash; <i>Charles Baudelaire</i></p><br /><p>
<b>The Alchemy of Sorrow</b><br>
</p>

<p>
One man lights you with his ardor,<br>
Another puts you in mourning, Nature!<br>
That which says to one: sepulcher!<br>
Says to another: life! glory!<br>
</p>

<p>
You have always frightened me, <br>
Hermes the unknown, you who help me. <br>
You make me the peer of Midas, <br>
The saddest of all alchemists;<br>
</p>

<p>
Through you I change gold to iron <br>
And make of paradise a hell; <br>
In the winding sheet of the clouds<br>
</p>

<p>
I discover a beloved corpse, <br>
And on the celestial shores <br>
I build massive sarcophagi.<br>
</p>

<p>
&mdash; William Aggeler, <i>The Flowers of Evil</i> (Fresno, CA: Academy Library Guild, 1954)<br>
</p>

<br>

<p>
<b>Alchemy of Sorrow</b>
</p>

<p>
One puts all nature into mourning,<br>
One lights her like a flaring sun &mdash; <br>
What whispers "Burial" to the one<br>
Cries to the other, "Life and Morning."<br>
</p>

<p>
The unknown Hermes who assists<br>
The role of Midas to reverse,<br>
And makes me by a subtle curse<br>
The saddest of all alchemists &mdash; <br>
</p>

<p>
By him, my paradise to hell,<br>
And gold to slag, is changed too well.<br>
The clouds are winding-sheets, and I,<br>
</p>

<p>
Bidding some dear-loved corpse farewell, <br>
Along the shore-line of the sky, <br>
Erect my vast sarcophagi.<br>
</p>

<p>
&mdash; Roy Campbell, <i>Poems of Baudelaire</i> (New York: Pantheon Books, 1952)<br>
</p>

<br>

<p>
<b>Alchimie de la douleur</b><br>
</p>

<p>
one lights thee with his flame, another<br>
puts in thee &mdash; Nature! &mdash; all his gloom!<br>
what says to this man: lo! the tomb!<br>
cries: life and splendour! to his brother.<br>
</p>

<p>
o mage unknown whose powers assist<br>
my art, and whom I always fear,<br>
thou makest me a Midas &mdash; peer<br>
of that most piteous alchemist;<br>
</p>

<p>
for 'tis through thee I turn my gold<br>
to iron, and in heaven behold<br>
my hell: beneath her cloud-palls I<br>
</p>

<p>
uncover corpses loved of old;<br>
and where the shores celestial die<br>
I carve vast tombs against the sky.<br>
</p>

<p>
&mdash; Lewis Piaget Shanks, <i>Flowers of Evil</i> (New York: Ives Washburn, 1931)<br>
</p>

<br>

<p>
<b>The Alchemy of Grief</b><br>
</p>

<p>
One, Nature! burns and makes thee bright, <br>
One gives thee weeds to mourn withal; <br>
And what to one is burial <br>
Is to the other life and light. <br>
</p>

<p>
The unknown Hermes who assists <br>
And always fills my heart with fear, <br>
Makes the mighty Midas' peer <br>
The saddest of the alchemists. <br>
</p>

<p>
Through him I make gold changeable <br>
To dross, and paradise to hell; <br>
Clouds for its corpse-cloths I descry. <br>
</p>

<p>
A stark dead body I love well, <br>
And in the gleaming fields on high <br>
I build immense sarcophagi. <br>
</p>

<p>
&mdash; Jack Collings Squire, <i>Poems and Baudelaire Flowers</i> (London: The New Age Press, Ltd, 1909)<br>
</p>

<br>

